				\begin{document}$$\hbox {WTe}_2$$\end{document} by DFT calculations. As it is clear from Fig. 1, 1T′ WTe2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\hbox {WTe}_2$$\end{document} has two non-equivalent Te atoms on its outermost surface, which we label Te(1) and Te(2). We considered two distinct types of vacancies, which are a single Te(1) vacancy and a single Te(2) vacancy. Furthermore, we studied a Te vacancy line defect, where Te atoms are removed diagonally in the unit cell. More complex defect geometries, such as the latter one, effectively further reduce the symmetry of the crystal, and it is envisioned that they can be fabricated experimentally by atom scale fabrications methods, such as focused electron or ion microscopy as well as scanning probe microscopy38,58,59. For the antisite defects, labelled A1 and A2, we investigated Te(1)-W and Te(2)-W antisites, where the positions of a Te(1) and a Te(2) atom with the neighboring W atom are exchanged. Finally, we also considered substitutional defects, where an oxygen molecule (O2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\hbox {O}_2$$\end{document}) replaces a Te atom. For this type of defect, four distinct geometries were considered: a Te(1)-O2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\hbox {O}_2$$\end{document} substitution with the oxygen molecule oriented parallel (perpendicular) to the surface and a Te(2)-O2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
